  "customIntroduction": "The smell reaches you before the light does — old ash, cold stone, and something underneath both that has no name. When the passage opens out, you see the room: a low-vaulted chamber of Old Empire cut-stone, its walls etched with the kind of administrative script the empire used for census rolls and population ledgers. Candles — unlit for what looks like decades — line the walls in iron brackets. And in the centre of the room, three figures stand around a stone table, heads bowed, as if still waiting for an order that was never rescinded.",
  "customContext": "The skeletons do not move when the party enters. That is the first wrong thing. The second is the table: the stone surface is covered in deep-cut tally marks — thousands of them, grouped in fives, running off the edges and continuing down the table legs and across the floor. Someone, or something, has been keeping count. The third wrong thing is the smell of fresh chalk dust, though there is no chalk in sight and no hand to hold it. Old Empire census-work. Population accounting. The Quota has roots older than anyone admits, and whatever ran the count in this chamber has not been told to stop. The skeletons are the last clerks of a bureaucracy that outlasted everything it served, and they will defend their ledger — and their count — with the only tools left to them.",
  "objective": "Destroy or drive off the skeletal clerks and determine what the tally marks record — the answer is worth knowing, and worth fearing.",
  "completionFlag": "bones_that_kept_counting_resolved",
